07839nam a22009855i 9780226382777DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20162016ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a9780226382777  a(DE-B1597)524565  a(OCoLC)956376527  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aQL698.95b.W49 2019 7aSCI0000002bisacsh04a59822300aWhy Birds Matter :bAvian Ecological Function and Ecosystem Services /ced. by Çagan H. Sekercioglu, Christopher J. Whelan, Daniel G. Wenny. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2016] 4c©2016  a1 online resource (368 p.) :b31 halftones, 6 line drawings, 8 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tForeword -- tPreface -- tChapter 1. Bird Ecosystem Services: Economic Ornithology for the 21st Century -- tChapter 2. Why Birds Matter Economically: Values, Markets, and Policies -- tChapter 3. Trophic Interaction Networks and Ecosystem Services -- tChapter 4. Pollination by Birds: A Functional Evaluation -- tChapter 5. Seed Dispersal by Fruit-Eating Birds -- tChapter 6. Dispersal of Plants by Waterbirds -- tChapter 7. Seed Dispersal by Corvids: Birds That Build Forests -- tChapter 8. Ecosystem Services Provided by Avian Scavengers -- tChapter 9. Nutrient Dynamics and Nutrient Cycling by Birds -- tChapter 10. Avian Ecosystem Engineers: Birds That Excavate Cavities -- tChapter 11. Avian Ecological Functions and Ecosystem Services in the Tropics -- tChapter 12. Why Birds Matter: Bird Ecosystem Services That Promote Biodiversity and Support Human Well-Being -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFor over one hundred years, ornithologists and amateur birders have jointly campaigned for the conservation of bird species, documenting not only birds’ beauty and extraordinary diversity, but also their importance to ecosystems worldwide. But while these avian enthusiasts have noted that birds eat fruit, carrion, and pests; spread seed and fertilizer; and pollinate plants, among other services, they have rarely asked what birds are worth in economic terms. In Why Birds Matter, an international collection of ornithologists, botanists, ecologists, conservation biologists, and environmental economists seeks to quantify avian ecosystem services—the myriad benefits that birds provide to humans. The first book to approach ecosystem services from an ornithological perspective, Why Birds Matter asks what economic value we can ascribe to those services, if any, and how this value should inform conservation. Chapters explore the role of birds in such important ecological dynamics as scavenging, nutrient cycling, food chains, and plant-animal interactions—all seen through the lens of human well-being—to show that quantifying avian ecosystem services is crucial when formulating contemporary conservation strategies. Both elucidating challenges and providing examples of specific ecosystem valuations and guidance for calculation, the contributors propose that in order to advance avian conservation, we need to appeal not only to hearts and minds, but also to wallets.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aBirdsxEcology. 0aBirds. 7aSCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  abird ecosystem services.  aeconomic commodification.  aeconomic ornithology.  anatural ecosystems.  apest control.  apollination.  ascavenging.  aseed dispersal.  atropical agroforestry.1 aAnderson, Sandra H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBeasley, James C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrochet, Anne-Laure, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBuechley, Evan R., econtributor.4ctb4https://i